---
// The orienting front door for the invisible-fields family: what these pages are, why no
// particles are visible, the one pipeline they all run, and every example as a stated
// correlation. Copy derives from docs/canonical/invisible-fields.md — the truth
// gate applies: nothing here claims more than the pages demonstrate.
import ExampleShell from "../../components/examples/ExampleShell.astro";
import { INVISIBLE_FIELDS } from "../../lib/invisible-fields.ts";
---

<ExampleShell
  title="Invisible fields — what these examples are"
  description="Twelve real interfaces where the field runs with no drawn surface: data becomes bodies, the field measures, and the measurements come back as typography, ink, and anchor."
  current="overview"
  mainClass="ex-overview"
  honesty={{
    source:
      "Every example is REAL data from a named public source (OpenAlex, Stack Overflow, CoinGecko, GitHub, npm, Hacker News, Launch Library, Open Library, ListenBrainz, Wikimedia). Each page names its own source and license.",
    snapshot:
      "Each source is a committed snapshot in src/data/examples/, stamped snapshotAt on refresh via scripts/snapshot-examples.mjs — builds never fetch, so they are deterministic.",
    liveRefresh:
      "Each page upgrades to live in the browser (wireLiveChip: a polite poll that skips hidden tabs and retires on failure). The committed snapshot is the SSR baseline and the no-JS truth.",
    notClaimed:
      "The field measures THE FIELD — emphasis, attention, decay, and relationship pressure in the interface. It never measures your users, judges the underlying data, or decides what is true. It makes a chosen signal legible; it does not choose the signal for you.",
  }}
>
  <header class="ev-head">
    <p class="ev-kicker">Invisible fields · the examples, explained</p>
    <h1>No particles. That is the point.</h1>
    <p class="ev-lede">
      Every page in this section is a real interface on real data — an inbox, a market, a
      backlog, a calendar. Each one runs a full physics field, and none of them draw it.
      The field is a <strong>measuring instrument</strong> here, not a picture: data becomes
      bodies, the field measures them every frame, and the measurements come back as CSS
      variables your styles consume. What you see — type gaining weight, ink deepening, a row
      sinking toward quiet — <em>is</em> the field.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="ev-sec">
    <h2>The one pipeline, all twelve pages</h2>
    <ol class="ev-pipeline ev-pipeline-big" aria-label="The invisible-field pipeline">
      <li><i>data</i><span>a real dataset — citations, listens, launches, incidents</span></li>
      <li><i>bodies</i><span>each record becomes a body: its quantity sets <code>data-strength</code> / mass</span></li>
      <li><i>measure</i><span>the field measures every frame — density, attention, load</span></li>
      <li><i>variables</i><span>measurements return as CSS custom properties (<code>--w</code>, <code>--d</code>, <code>--field-attention</code>, <code>--load</code>)</span></li>
      <li><i>you see</i><span>CSS renders them: weight, ink, anchor, fill — no canvas, no swarm</span></li>
    </ol>
    <p class="ev-note">
      The page-level lesson, true of all twelve: <strong>the field does not care about the
      layout; it measures whatever geometry you give it.</strong> A list, a grid, a front page,
      a calendar — same instrument, different surface.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="ev-sec">
    <h2>Why this beats hand-rolling it</h2>
    <p>
      Each page replaces a category of code you would otherwise write and maintain: the scoring
      scheme and the re-sort pass, the staleness timers, the priority tiers that drift until a
      meeting renormalizes them. Here the question each of those answered — <em>what matters,
      what's related, what's gone stale</em> — is answered continuously by the field, and the
      readout is simply already current. The scope is honest: the field measures <em>the
      field</em> — emphasis, attention, decay in the interface — never your users, your data
      layer, or your analytics.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="ev-sec">
    <h2>Every example, as a correlation</h2>
    <ul class="ev-index">
      {
        INVISIBLE_FIELDS.map((f) => (
          <li>
            <a href={f.href}>
              <b>{f.name}</b>
              <span class="ev-index-map">
                {f.becomes} → <em>{f.see}</em>
              </span>
            </a>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="ev-sec">
    <h2>The honesty contract</h2>
    <p>
      Every page states its data provenance in a chip — <code>live · checked Ns ago</code>
      after a successful refresh, <code>snapshot · date</code> otherwise — and each one's
      explainer band names exactly which variables the field writes. If a page can't prove a
      claim live, the claim isn't made.
    </p>
  </section>
</ExampleShell>
